<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[812,1452,1104,1224]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,949,1104,1129]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,928,1105,1129]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
The new species is similar to the female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Deeleman-Reinhold, 1995" authorityName="Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityYear="1995" class="Arachnida" family="Ochyroceratidae" genus="Speocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leclerci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">S. leclerci</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Deeleman-Reinhold, C" box="[899,1183,1137,1160]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 103" refId="ref5819" refString="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L., 1995. The Ochyroceratidae of the Indo- Pacific region (Araneae). Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, (suppl.), 2: 1 - 103." type="journal article" year="1995">Deeleman-Reinhold, 1995</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the presence of eyes, the straight metatarsus IV, and the larger body size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[812,1451,1264,1416]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,937,1264,1289]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,917,1265,1289]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Remarks.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
Most genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fage" authorityYear="1912" box="[1117,1293,1265,1288]" class="Arachnida" family="Ochyroceratidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ochyroceratidae</taxonomicName>
are frequently met in caves, yet most of them do not show any morphological adaptations. The pale body color and especially the long legs of this new species are typical morphological adaptation to cave environment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[812,1452,1456,1864]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,969,1456,1481]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,946,1457,1481]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Description.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
Females: Total length 1.36–1.39. Carapace 0.59–0.62 long, 0.46–0.48 wide; abdomen 0.76–0.80 long, 0.53–0.58 wide. Carapace pale yellow without pattern, only near the eyes with some pigment, but nearly absent in 
<specimenCount pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
. Sternum, abdomen and legs pale yellow. Chelicerae unmodified. Legs spineless, metatarsus IV as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityYear="1995" box="[812,919,1649,1672]" class="Arachnida" family="Ochyroceratidae" genus="Speocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leclerci">
<emphasis box="[812,919,1649,1672]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">S. leclerci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, distally provided with three pairs of small strong setae ventrally, but straight. Leg measurements: I 3.43 (1.02, 0.19, 1.09, 0.78, 0.35); II 3.15 (0.98, 0.18, 0.94, 0.70, 0.35); III 2.70 (0.82, 0.19, 0.73, 0.64, 0.32); IV 3.53 (1.08, 0.19, 1.05, 0.85, 0.36). Leg formula: 4 1 2 3. Palp measurements: 0.62 (0.20, 0.09, 0.15, 0.18). Chitinous ducts very long, surrounding the abdomen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[812,995,1905,1928]" box="[812,995,1905,1928]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Male: Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="etymology">
